# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-deaf-community
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan was recognised by the Australian government as a "community language other than English" and the preferred language of the deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] However, this recognition has yet to filter through to many institutions, government departments, and professionals who work with deaf people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The emerging status of Auslan has gone hand-in-hand with the advancement of the deaf community in Australia, beginning in the early 1980s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In 1982, the registration of the first sign language interpreters by NAATI, a newly established regulatory body for interpreting and translating, accorded a sense of legitimacy to Auslan, furthered by the publishing of the first dictionary of Auslan in 1989 (Johnston, 1989).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Boosted by the 1992 enactment of the federal Disability Discrimination Act, Auslan/English interpreters are also increasingly provided in tertiary education.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Today there is a growing number of courses teaching Auslan as a second language, from an elective language subject offered by some secondary schools to a two-year full-time diploma at TAFE.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan content on television in Australia is limited.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] For some time, "Deaf TV", which was entirely in Auslan and was produced by deaf volunteers, aired on community television station Channel 31 in Melbourne.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Auslan experienced a period of increased visibility through press conferences from federal and state leaders and health officials, which invariably featured Auslan interpreters.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Since 2020, the ABC News channel's Sunday 5pm bulletin has included Auslan interpretation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan Day is celebrated on 13 April each year.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] This date was chosen as the anniversary of the publication of the first Auslan dictionary in 1989.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The Young Australian of the Year for 2015, Drisana Levitzke-Gray, is a strong proponent of Auslan and, in her acceptance speech using Auslan, called on the Government of Australia, and Australians, to learn and use Auslan as a natural language, as a human right for Australians.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan evolved from sign language varieties brought to Australia during the nineteenth century from Britain and Ireland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The earliest record of a deaf Australian was convict Elizabeth Steel, who arrived in 1790 on the Second Fleet ship "Lady Juliana".
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] There is as yet no historical evidence, however, that she used a sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] One of the first known signing Deaf immigrants was the engraver John Carmichael who arrived in Sydney in 1825 from Edinburgh.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] He had been to a Deaf school there, and was known as a good storyteller in sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Thirty-five years later, in 1860, a school for the deaf was established by another deaf Scotsman, Thomas Pattison—the Royal Institute for Deaf and Blind Children in New South Wales.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In Victoria just a few weeks later, the Victorian College for the Deaf was founded by a deaf Englishman, Frederick J Rose, who had been educated at the Old Kent Road School in London.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] These schools and others had an enormous role in the development of Auslan, as they were the first contact with sign language for many deaf children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Because they were residential boarding schools, they provided ample opportunity for the language to thrive, even though in many schools, signing was banned from the classroom for much of the 20th century.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Irish Sign Language (ISL) also had an influence on the development of Auslan, as it was used in Roman Catholic deaf schools until the 1950s, especially in Sydney.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The first Catholic school for deaf children was established in 1875 by Irish nuns.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] As such, like Auslan evolving from BSL, Australian Irish Sign Language (or AISL) was born.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Unlike British Sign Language, both ISL and AISL use a one-handed alphabet originating in French Sign Language (LSF), and although this alphabet has now almost disappeared from Australia, some initialised signs from the ISL/AISL manual alphabet are still used in Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The language contact post-secondary education between Australian ISL users and 'Australian BSL' users accounts for some of the dialectal differences seen between modern BSL and Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In more recent times, Auslan has seen a significant amount of lexical borrowing from American Sign Language (ASL), especially in signs for technical terms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Some of these arose from the Signed English educational philosophies of the 1970s and 80s, when a committee looking for signs with direct equivalence to English words found them in ASL and/or in invented English-based signed systems used in North America and introduced them in the classroom.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] ASL contains many signs initialised from an alphabet which was also derived from LSF, and Auslan users, already familiar with the related ISL alphabet, accepted many of the new signs easily.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Tertiary education in the US for some deaf Australian adults also accounts for some ASL borrowings found in modern Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Previously, Auslan had been said to be OSV, but more recent scholars have said that this idea is a false-equivalent of Auslan with spoken languages and that using anchor signs is not the same as word order.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In general, word order in Auslan takes into account context and fluidity between signs being used, being less rigid than many spoken languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Rather, Auslan instead follows the clause/word order of TTC—Time, topic, comment.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The frequency of SVO in Auslan may come from code-switching with English (with very high bilingualism for Auslan users), as it is more common with "loan words (signs), English-based idiomatic phrases [and] fingerspelling" as well as by those who learned Auslan later in life.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In question phrases, the question word must always be at the end in Auslan in open questions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] This word order is the same for both questions and statements, with questions in Auslan formed by either adding a question word at the end of a clause TOM KICKED PETER WHY or using nonmanual features of a questioning expression.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Verbs in Auslan which are *depicting signs* use head-marking to show the semantic role of the arguments, rather than subject/object.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] An example of this is the word *give*, which involves an actor and a recipient.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Both of these arguments can be expressed on the verb by using signing space.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Verb predicates can be formed by using individual vocabulary words in sequential order (more commonly used by anglophones who speak Auslan as a second language) or using depicting signs, which can "blur" word order, as it allows for multiple signs to be used at once.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] This is generally a mark of high competence and fluency in the language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Lexicalisation of common predicates is common, and compounding is the most common way that new lexical items are produced.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan is a zero-copula language, which means that the verb *to be* is not used at all except when quoting English (in which it is finger-spelt).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan replaces copula with interrogatives for certain phrase types, sometimes in this context called "rhetorical questions" or "modifiers", using non-manual features to express that it is a statement rather than a question.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The interrogatives of Auslan are more or less direct translations to English ones, with WHY used for this purpose sometimes translated as BECAUSE.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Pronouns are established using the signing space, either arbitrary (for non-present people/things) or iconic.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] For example, "I will give you the doll tomorrow" would be signed as TOMORROW DOLL GIVE, with the sign GIVE starting at the speaker's body and finishing at the receiver's.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The use of signing space also makes all pronouns non-gendered.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] It is sometimes wrongly assumed that English-speaking countries share a single sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan is a natural language distinct from spoken or written English.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Its grammar and vocabulary often do not have direct English equivalents and vice versa.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] However, English, as the dominant language in Australia, has had a significant influence on Auslan, especially through manual forms such as fingerspelling and (more recently) Signed English.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] It is difficult to sign Auslan fluently while speaking English, as the word order may be different, and there is often no direct sign-to-word equivalence.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] However, mouthing of an English word together with a sign may serve to clarify when one sign may have several English equivalents.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In some cases, the mouth gesture that accompanies a sign may not reflect the equivalent translation in English (e.g. a sign meaning "thick" may be accompanied by a mouth gesture that does not resemble any English word).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] A two-handed manual alphabet, identical to the one used in British Sign Language and New Zealand Sign Language, is integral to Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] This alphabet is used for fingerspelling proper nouns such as personal or place names, common nouns for everyday objects, and English words, especially technical terms, for which there is no widely used sign.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Fingerspelling can also be used for emphasis, clarification, or, sometimes extensively, by English-speaking learners of Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The proportion of fingerspelling versus signs varies with the context and the age of the signer.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] A recent small-scale study puts fingerspelled words in Auslan conversations at about 10% of all lexical items, roughly equal to ASL and higher than many other sign languages, such as New Zealand Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The proportion is higher in older signers, suggesting that the use of fingerspelling has diminished over time.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Schembri and Johnston (2007) found that the most commonly fingerspelled words in Auslan include "so", "to", "if", "but" and "do".
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Some signs also feature an English word's initial letter as a handshape from a one- or two-handed manual alphabet and use it within a sign.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] For example, part of the sign for "Canberra" incorporates the letter "C".
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Australasian Signed English was created in the late 1970s to represent English words and grammar, using mostly Auslan signs together with some additional contrived signs, as well as borrowings from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] It was used largely in education for teaching English to deaf children or for *discussing* English in academic contexts, and it is not clear to what extent this continues to be the case.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] It was thought to be much easier for hearing teachers and parents to learn another mode of English than to learn a new language with a complex spatial grammar such as Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The use of Signed English in schools is controversial with some in the deaf community who regard Signed English as a contrived and unnatural artificially constructed language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Signed English has now been largely rejected by deaf communities in Australia and its use in education is dwindling; however, a number of its signs have made their way into normal use.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Unlike oral languages, only a minority of deaf children acquire their language from their parents (about 4 or 5% have deaf parents).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Most acquire Auslan from deaf peers at school or later through deaf community networks.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Many learn Auslan as a "delayed" first language in adolescence or adulthood, after attempting to learn English (or another spoken/written language) without the exposure necessary to properly acquire it.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The deaf community often distinguish between "oral deaf" who grew up in an oral or signed English educational environment without Auslan, and those "*Deaf* Deaf" who learnt Auslan at an early age from deaf parents or at a deaf school.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Regardless of their background, many deaf adults consider Auslan to be their first or primary language, and see themselves as users of English as a second language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan exhibits a high degree of variation, determined by the signer's age, educational background, and regional origin, and the signing community is very accepting of a wide range of individual differences in signing style.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Standard dialects arise through the support of institutions, such as the media, education, government and the law.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] As this support has not existed for most sign languages, coupled with the lack of a widely used written form and communications technologies, Auslan has probably diverged much more rapidly from BSL than Australian English has from British English.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan was introduced to Papua New Guinea, where it mixed with local or home sign and Tok Pisin to produce Papua New Guinean Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Sign languages related to Auslan also appear to be used in some other parts of the Asia-Pacific, such as in Fiji.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Linguists often regard Auslan as having two major dialects—Northern (Queensland and New South Wales), and Southern (Victoria, Tasmania, South Australia, and Western Australia).
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The vocabulary of the two dialects traditionally differed significantly, with different signs used even for very common concepts such as colours, animals, and days of the week; differences in grammar appear to be slight.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Before schools were established elsewhere, deaf children attended one of these two initial schools, and brought signs back to their own states.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] As schools opened up in each state, new signs also developed in the dormitories and playgrounds of these institutions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] As a result, Auslan users can identify more precise regional varieties (e.g., "Sydney sign", "Melbourne sign", "Perth sign", "Adelaide sign" and "Brisbane sign"), and even vocabulary that may have been unique to individual schools.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] In a conversation between two strangers, one from Melbourne and the other from Perth, it is likely that one will use a small number of signs unfamiliar to the other, despite both belonging to the same "southern dialect".
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Signers can often identify which school someone went to, even within a few short utterances.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] A number of Indigenous Australian sign languages exist, unrelated to Auslan, such as Warlpiri Sign Language and Yolngu Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] They occur in the southern, central, and western desert regions, coastal Arnhem Land, some islands of the north coast, the western side of Cape York Peninsula, and on some Torres Strait Islands.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] They have also been noted as far south as the Murray River.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Deaf Indigenous people of Far North Queensland (extending from Yarrabah to Cape York) form a distinct signing community using a dialect of Auslan; it has features of Indigenous sign languages and gestural systems as well as signs and grammar of Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] Auslan has no written form; in the past transcribing Auslan was largely an academic exercise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] The first Auslan dictionaries used either photographs or drawings with motion arrows to describe signs; more recently, technology has made possible the use of short video clips on CD-ROM or online dictionaries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/auslan] SignWriting, however, has its adherents in Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] The deaf community in Australia is a diverse cultural and linguistic minority group.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Deaf communities have many distinctive cultural characteristics, some of which are shared across many countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] These characteristics include language, values and behaviours.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] The Australian deaf community relies primarily on Australian Sign Language, or Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Those in the Australian deaf community experience some parts of life differently than those in the broader hearing world, such as access to education and health care.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Australian Sign Language, also known as Auslan, is the primary signed language for deaf Australians.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] It is hard to tell how many signing deaf people are in Australia as much information is unavailable, and what information is available is largely out of date.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Auslan is the native languages of a few deaf signers in Australia, although it is the preferred language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] It's common for deaf Australians to not learn Auslan until they are in school with other deaf children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] In some cases, they do not learn it or pick it up until adulthood because they did not go to a specialized school for the deaf where there would be more people to learn from or practice with.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Signers in Australia use a combination of Auslan and natural sign language, signed English and contact signing to communicate best between each other, including with hearing people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Not all deaf signers are especially proficient in English, and English and Australian Sign Language are not interchangeable and are, in fact, entirely separate languages although they have influenced one another.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Those who know Auslan and English would be considered bilingual.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Although some schools for the deaf teach using Auslan, English is the written language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Auslan shows up in many ways through different dialects or accents, and the way someone may sign Auslan can be affected by several external factors such as region, religion, age and school.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] People of the Australian deaf community are usually someone who acquired deafness or significant hearing impairments in childhood and can sign in Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Those who acquired deafness or hearing differences in adulthood likely have a good understanding of spoken language, namely English, and may be able to read lips or communicate with most people relatively easily.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] The number of deaf people in Australia may be configured using data from hearing tests done at birth, although this does not guarantee that said persons know how to sign Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Being a part of the Australian deaf community may include a robust social life with other deaf people, although deaf people are a part of the larger hearing world as well.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Signing is used in schools, clubs, and organizations directly between members or through interpreters.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Deaf children are typically not born from deaf parents, and therefore likely do not learn much signing from their parents at the time that is critical for language development.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] They likely pick it up when they enter school, assuming that said school has other deaf children or teaches Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] More often, schools do not teach Auslan unless it is a specialized school for deaf children depending on the mode of teaching used.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Even so, teachers of Auslan may have learned slightly outdated Auslan which may affect the quality of education of Deaf students who rely on signing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Bilingual programs are available to deaf students in Australia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] While bilingual models of teaching exist, they are relatively recent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Deaf children often learned or currently learn Auslan or another form of signed language during social events like recess.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Currently, it is often that students in mainstream schooling are taken out of classrooms and taught one-on-one, which may impede their socialization with other students.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Interpreters are not always available, and the quality of the sign language in the classroom varies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Health care related to hearing impairments in Australia includes hearing devices like hearing aids and cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] Implantation of cochlear implants for deaf children is relatively high in Australia compared to the rest of the world, and around 80% of significantly deaf or hard of hearing children receive one.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] There are notable shortages of Auslan interpreters trained to give medical information in the sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/australian-deaf-community] There are also some places in Australia where accommodations for deaf patients, such as appointment booking with text or email; and limitations such as additional fees for interpreters or longer appointments, and additional patient responsibilities like providing one's own interpreter.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A **cochlear implant** (**CI**) is a surgically implanted neuroprosthesis that provides a person who has moderate-to-profound sensorineural hearing loss with sound perception.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] With the help of therapy, cochlear implants may allow for improved speech understanding in both quiet and noisy environments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A CI bypasses acoustic hearing by direct electrical stimulation of the auditory nerve.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Through everyday listening and auditory training, cochlear implants allow both children and adults to learn to interpret those signals as speech and sound.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The outside component is the sound processor, which contains microphones, electronics that include digital signal processor (DSP) chips, battery, and a coil that transmits a signal to the implant across the skin.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] It is generally worn behind the ear, though some self-contained sound processors take the form of a pebble-shaped unit worn directly on the side of the head over the implant site, held in place by magnetic attraction to the internal implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The sound processor could also be attached to clothing, for example, in the case of young children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The inside component is the actual implant, which contains a coil to receive signals, electronics, and an array of electrodes that stimulate the cochlear nerve, which is placed into the cochlea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The surgical procedure is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Surgical risks are minimal, and most individuals will undergo outpatient surgery and go home the same day.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, some individuals will experience dizziness, and on rare occasions, tinnitus or facial nerve bruising.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] From the early days of implants in the 1970s and 1980s, speech perception via an implant improved greatly, though gains have plateaued since the introduction of modern sound coding strategies in the 1990s.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] More than 200,000 people in the United States had received a CI through 2019.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Many users of modern implants gain reasonable to good hearing and speech perception skills post-implantation, especially when combined with lipreading.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] One of the challenges that remain with these implants is that hearing and speech understanding skills after implantation show a wide range of variation across individual implant users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Factors such as age of implantation, parental involvement and education level, duration and cause of hearing loss, how the implant is situated in the cochlea, the overall health of the cochlear nerve, and individual capabilities of relearning are considered to contribute to this variation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] André Djourno and Charles Eyriès invented the original cochlear implant in 1957.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Their design distributed stimulation using a single channel.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] William House also invented a cochlear implant in 1961.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] White implanted a single-channel electrode in a patient's cochlea at Stanford University.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, research indicated that these single-channel cochlear implants were of limited usefulness because they cannot stimulate different areas of the cochlea at different times to allow differentiation between low and mid-to-high frequencies as required for detecting speech.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The next step in the development of the CI was its clinical trial on a cohort of patients.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In the late 1960s, Robin Michelson and colleague Melvin Bartz constructed a cochlear device with biocompatible materials that can be implanted in human patients.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This system was implanted in 4 patients, and the report of the hearing results was a watershed for clinically applicable cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Robin Michelson, Robert Schindler, and Michael Merzenich at the University of California, San Francisco (UCSF), conducted these experiments in 1970 and 1971.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Michelson, a clinical pioneer, and Merzenich, a talented basic scientist with a solid foundation in neurophysiology, were integral in the development of the UCSF cochlear implant team.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Michelson was recognized for implanting a single-channel device into a congenitally deaf woman.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] She demonstrated auditory sensations from stimulation, as well as pitch perception for stimulus frequencies less than 600 Hz.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Unfortunately, this patient had no word recognition.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] His pioneering work was presented, but not well-received at the 1971 annual meeting of the American Otological Society (Michelson, 1971 and Merzenich et al., 1973).
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In 1973, the first international conference on the "electrical stimulation of the acoustic nerve as a treatment for profound sensorineural deafness in man" was organized in San Francisco.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] NASA engineer Adam Kissiah started working in the mid-1970s on the design for a cochlear implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Kissiah used his knowledge learned while working as an electronics instrumentation engineer for NASA.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This work took place over three years, when Kissiah would spend his lunch breaks and evenings in Kennedy Space Center's technical library, studying the impact of engineering principles on the inner ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In 1977, NASA helped Kissiah obtain a patent for his cochlear implant; Kissiah later sold the patent rights.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A commercial product based on Kissiah's design, developed by BIOSTIM Inc., was tested but failed to reach the marketplace.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The Hochmairs' 1977 implant, though an early milestone, did not in its original 8-channel form lead directly to the modern device.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Testing of that first system failed to produce open speech understanding and the Hochmairs changed their approach.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] It was Clark's multi-channel design, commercialized as the Nucleus device by Cochlear Limited, that became the first multi-channel cochlear implant to receive FDA approval in 1985, and successive iterations of the Nucleus device went on to become the most widely used cochlear implants in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Excitation of the cochlear nerve by the neurotransmitter sends signals to the brain, which creates the experience of sound.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] With an implant, instead, the devices pick up sound and digitize it, convert that digitized sound into electrical signals, and transmit those signals to electrodes embedded in the cochlea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The electrodes electrically stimulate the cochlear nerve, causing it to send signals to the brain.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Several manufacturers currently have a totally implantable cochlear implant (TICI) in development or undergoing clinical testing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This new type of cochlear implant incorporates all the current external components of an audio processor into the internal implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The lack of external components makes the implant invisible from the outside and also means it is less likely to be damaged or broken.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] On the other side, the development of a TICI faces especially two technical hurdles: the energy supply and the design of the implantable microphone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Initial clinical trials of TICIs have demonstrated safety and comparable performance to conventional cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A study involving a research TICI indicated that users experienced high levels of hearing performance, although some challenges with microphone sensitivity were noted.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Most modern cochlear implants can be used with a range of assistive listening devices (ALDs), which help people to hear better in challenging listening situations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] These situations could include talking on the phone, watching TV, or listening to a speaker or teacher.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] With an ALD, the sound from devices, including mobile phones, or from an external microphone is sent to the audio processor directly, rather than being picked up by the audio processor's microphone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This direct transmission improves the sound quality for the user, making it easier to talk on the phone or stream music.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] ALDs come in many forms, such as neckloops, pens, and specialist battery pack covers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Modern ALDs are usually able to receive sound from any Bluetooth device, including phones and computers, before transmitting it wirelessly to the audio processor.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Most cochlear implants are also compatible with older ALD technology, such as a telecoil.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Implantation in children and adults can be done safely with few surgical complications, and most individuals will undergo outpatient surgery and go home the same day.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Occasionally, the very young, the very old, or patients with a significant number of medical diseases at once may remain for overnight observation in the hospital.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The procedure can be performed in an ambulatory surgery center in healthy individuals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The surgical procedure most often used to implant the device is called mastoidectomy with facial recess approach (MFRA).
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The procedure is usually done under general anesthesia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Complications of the procedure are rare, but include mastoiditis, otitis media (acute or with effusion), shifting of the implanted device requiring a second procedure, damage to the facial nerve, damage to the chorda tympani, and wound infections.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Cochlear implantation surgery is considered a clean procedure with an infection rate of less than 3%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Guidelines suggest that routine prophylactic antibiotics are not required.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, the potential cost of a postoperative infection is high (including the possibility of implant loss); therefore, a single preoperative intravenous injection of antibiotics is recommended.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The rate of complications is about 12% for minor complications and 3% for major complications; major complications include infections, facial paralysis, and device failure.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Although up to 20 new cases of post-CI bacterial meningitis occur annually worldwide, data demonstrates a reducing incidence.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] To avoid the risk of bacterial meningitis, the CDC recommends that adults and children undergoing CI receive age-appropriate vaccines that generate antibodies to Streptococcus pneumoniae.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The rate of transient facial nerve palsy is estimated to be approximately 1%.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Device failure requiring reimplantation is estimated to occur 2.5–6% of the time.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Up to one-third of people experience disequilibrium, vertigo, or vestibular weakness lasting more than one week after the procedure; in people under 70, these symptoms generally resolve over weeks to months, but in people over 70, the problems tend to persist.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Other approaches, such as going through the suprameatal triangle, are used.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A systematic literature review published in 2016 found that studies comparing the two approaches were generally small, not randomized, and retrospective, so they were not useful for making generalizations; it is not known which approach is safer or more effective.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] With the increased utilization of endoscopic ear surgery as popularized by Muaaz Tarabichi, there have been multiple published reports on the use of endoscopic technique in cochlear implant surgery.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, this has been motivated by marketing, and there is clear indication of increased morbidity associated with this technique as reported by Tarabichi.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As cochlear implant surgical techniques have advanced over the last four decades, the global complication rate for CI surgery in both children and adults has decreased from more than 35% in 1991 to less than 10% at present.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The risk of postoperative facial nerve injury has also decreased over the last several decades to less than 1%, most of which demonstrated complete return of function within six months.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The rate of permanent paralysis is approximately 1 per 1,000 surgeries and likely less than that in experienced CI centers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The majority of complications following CI surgery are minor, requiring only conservative medical management or prolongation of hospital stay.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Less than 5% of all complications are major, resulting in surgical intervention or readmission to the hospital.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Reported rates of revision cochlear implant surgery vary in adults and children from 3.8% to 8%, with the most common indications being device failure, infection, and migration of the implant or electrode.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Disequilibrium and vertigo after CI surgery can occur, but the symptoms tend to be mild and short-lived.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] CI rarely results in significant or persistent adverse effects on the vestibular system when hearing conservation surgical techniques are practiced.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Moreover, gait and postural stability may actually improve post-implantation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Cochlear implant outcomes can be measured using speech recognition ability and functional improvements measured using patient-reported outcome measures.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] While the degree of improvement after cochlear implantation may vary, the majority of patients who receive cochlear implants demonstrate a significant improvement in speech recognition ability compared to their preoperative condition.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Multiple meta-analyses of the literature from 2018 showed that CI users have large improvements in quality of life after cochlear implantation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This improvement occurs in many different facets of life that extend beyond communication, including improved ability to engage in social activities, decreased mental effort from listening, and improved environmental sound awareness.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Deaf adolescents with cochlear implants attending mainstream educational settings report high levels of scholastic self-esteem, friendship self-esteem, and global self-esteem.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2019 study found that bilateral cochlear implantation was widely regarded as the most beneficial hearing intervention for acceptable candidates, although it is more likely to be performed in children than adults.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The study also found that the efficacy of bilateral implantation could be improved by enhancing communication between the two implants and by developing sound coding strategies specifically for bilateral users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Early research reviews found that the ability to communicate in spoken language was better the earlier the implantation was performed.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The reviews also found that, overall, while cochlear implants provide open-set speech understanding for the majority of implanted profoundly hearing-impaired children, it was not possible to accurately predict the specific outcome of the given implanted child.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Research since then has reported long-term socio-economic benefits for children as well as audiological outcomes, including improved sound localization and speech perception.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A consensus statement from the European Bilateral Pediatric Cochlear Implant Forum also confirmed the importance of bilateral cochlear implantation in children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In adults, new research shows that bilateral implantation can improve quality of life and speech intelligibility in quiet and noise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2015 review examined whether CI implantation to treat people with bilateral hearing loss had any effect on tinnitus.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Further research found that the electrical stimulation of the CI is at least partly responsible for the general reduction in symptoms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2019 study found that although tinnitus suppression in patients with CIs is multifactorial, simply having the CI switched on without any audiological input (while standing alone in a soundproof booth) reduced the symptoms of tinnitus.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This would suggest that it is the electrical stimulation that explains the decrease in tinnitus symptoms for many patients, and not only the increased access to sound.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2015 literature review on the use of CI for people with auditory neuropathy spectrum disorder found that, as of that date, description and diagnosis of the condition were too heterogeneous to make clear claims about whether CI is a safe and effective way to manage it.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The data for cochlear implant outcomes in older adults differs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2016 research study found that age at implantation was highly correlated with postoperative speech understanding performance for various test measures.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In this study, people who were implanted at age 65 or older performed significantly worse on speech perception testing in quiet and in noisy conditions compared to younger CI users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Other studies have shown different outcomes, with some reporting that adults implanted at the age of 65 and older showed audiological and speech discrimination outcomes similar to younger adults.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] While cochlear implants demonstrate substantial benefit across all age groups, results will depend on cognitive factors that are ultimately highly age-dependent.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, studies have documented the benefit of cochlear implants in octogenarians.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The effects of aging on central auditory processing abilities are thought to play an important role in impacting an individual's speech perception with a cochlear implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The Lancet reported that untreated hearing loss in adults is the number one modifiable risk factor for dementia.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In 2017, a study also reported that adults using a cochlear implant had significantly improved cognitive outcomes, including working memory, reaction time, and cognitive flexibility, compared to people who were waiting to receive a cochlear implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Prolonged duration of deafness is another factor that is thought to have a negative impact on overall speech understanding outcomes for CI users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, a study found no statistical difference in the speech understanding abilities of CI patients over 65 who had been hearing impaired for 30 years or more prior to implantation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In general, outcomes for CI patients are dependent upon the individual's level of motivation, expectations, exposure to speech stimuli, and consistent participation in aural rehabilitation programs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2016 systematic review of CI for people with unilateral hearing loss (UHL) found that of the studies conducted and published, none were randomized, only one evaluated a control group, and no study was blinded.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] After eliminating multiple uses of the same subjects, the authors found that 137 people with UHL had received a CI.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] It appeared to improve speech perception and to reduce tinnitus.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In terms of quality of life, several studies have shown that cochlear implants are beneficial in many aspects of quality of life, including communication improvements and positive effects on social, emotional, psychological, and physical well-being.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A 2017 narrative review also concluded that the quality of life scores of children using cochlear implants were comparable to those of children without hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Studies involving adults of all ages reported significant improvement in QoL after implantation when compared to adults with hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This was often independent of audiological performance.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As of October 2010, approximately 188,000 individuals had been fitted with cochlear implants worldwide.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As of December 2012, the same publication cited approximately 324,000 cochlear implant devices having been surgically implanted.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In the U.S., roughly 58,000 devices were implanted in adults and 38,000 in children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As of 2016, the Ear Foundation in the United Kingdom estimates the number of cochlear implant recipients in the world to be about 600,000.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The American Cochlear Implant Alliance estimates that 217,000 people received CIs in the United States through the end of 2019.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Cochlear implantation includes the medical device as well as related services and procedures, including preoperative testing, the surgery, and aftercare that includes audiology and speech language pathology services.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] These are provided over time by a team of clinicians with specialized training.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] All of these services, as well as the cochlear implant device and related peripherals, are part of the medical intervention and are typically covered by health insurance in the United States and many areas of the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In many countries around the world, the cost of cochlear implantation and aftercare is covered by health insurance.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, financial factors impact the evaluation selection process.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Children with public health insurance or no health insurance are less likely to receive the implant before 2 years old.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In the US, as cochlear implants have become more commonplace and accepted as a valuable and cost effective health intervention, insurance coverage has expanded to include private insurance, Medicare, Tricare, the VA System, other federal health plans, and Medicaid.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In September 2022 the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services expanded coverage of cochlear implants for appropriate candidates under Medicare.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Candidates must demonstrate limited benefit with appropriately fit hearing aids, but with criteria now defined by test scores of less than or equal to 60% correct in the best-aided listening condition on recorded tests of open-set sentence recognition.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Just as there is with any medical procedure, there are typically co-pays, which vary depending upon the insurance plan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In Germany and Austria, the cost is covered by most health insurance organizations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] 6.1% of the world population live with hearing loss, and it is predicted that by 2050, more than 900 million people around the globe will have a disabling hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] According to a WHO report, unaddressed hearing loss costs the world 980 billion dollars annually.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Particularly hard hit are the healthcare and educational sectors, as well as societal costs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] 53% of these costs are attributable to low- and middle-income countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The WHO reports that cochlear implants have been shown to be a cost-effective way to mitigate the challenges of hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In a low-to-middle-income setting, every dollar invested in unilateral cochlear implants has a return on investment of 1.46 dollars.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This rises to a return on investment of 4.09 dollars in an upper-middle-income setting.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A study in Colombia assessed the lifetime investments made in 68 children who received cochlear implants at an early age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Taking into account the cost of the device and any other medical costs, follow-up, speech therapy, batteries and travel, each child required an average investment of US$99 000 over the course of their life (assuming a life span of 78 years for women and 72 years for men).
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The study concluded that for every dollar invested in rehabilitation of a child with a cochlear implant, there was a return on investment of US$2.07.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As of 2021, four cochlear implant devices approved for use in the United States are manufactured by Cochlear Limited, the Advanced Bionics division of Sonova, MED-EL, and Oticon Medical.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] As of June 2023, Oticon Medical changed ownership to Cochlear Ltd.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] In Europe, Africa, Asia, South America, and Canada, an additional device manufactured by Neurelec (later acquired by Oticon Medical) was available.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] A device made by Nurotron (China) was also available in some parts of the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Each manufacturer has adapted some of the successful innovations of the other companies to its own devices.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] There is no consensus that any one of these implants is superior to the others.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Users of all devices report a wide range of performance after implantation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Much of the strongest objection to cochlear implants has come from within the deaf community, some of whom are pre-lingually deaf people whose first language is a sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Some in the deaf community call cochlear implants audist and an affront to their culture, which, as they view it, is a minority threatened by the hearing majority.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This is an old problem for the deaf community, going back as far as the 18th century with the argument of manualism vs. oralism.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This is consistent with medicalization and the standardization of the "normal" body in the 19th century, when differences between normal and abnormal began to be debated.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] It is important to consider the sociocultural context, particularly in regard to the deaf community, which has its own unique language and culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This accounts for the cochlear implant being seen as an affront to their culture, as many do not believe that deafness is something that needs to be cured.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, it has also been argued that this does not necessarily have to be the case: the cochlear implant can act as a tool deaf people can use to access the "hearing world" without losing their deaf identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Cochlear implants for congenitally deaf children are most effective when implanted at a young age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Children who have had confirmed severe hearing loss can receive the implant as young as 9 months old.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Evidence shows that deaf children of deaf parents (or with fluent signers as daily caregivers) learn signed language as effectively as hearing peers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Some deaf-community advocates recommend that all deaf children should learn sign language from birth, but more than 90% of deaf children are born to hearing parents.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Since it takes years to become fluent in sign language, deaf children who grow up without amplification such as hearing aids or cochlear implants will not have daily access to fluent language models in households without fluent signers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Critics of cochlear implants from deaf cultures also assert that the cochlear implant and the subsequent therapy often become the focus of the child's identity at the expense of language acquisition and ease of communication in sign language and deaf identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] They believe that measuring a child's success only by their mastery of speech will lead to a poor self-image as "disabled" (because the implants do not produce normal hearing) rather than having the healthy self-concept of a proudly deaf person.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, these assertions are not supported by research.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The first children to receive cochlear implants as infants are only in their 20s (as of 2020), and anecdotal evidence points to a high level of satisfaction in this cohort, most of whom don't consider their deafness their primary identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Children with cochlear implants are most likely to be educated with listening and spoken language, without sign language, and are often not educated with other deaf children who use sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Cochlear implants have been one of the technological and social factors implicated in the decline of sign languages in the developed world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Some Deaf activists have labeled the widespread implantation of children as a cultural genocide.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] However, there is disagreement among researchers about the effectiveness of methods using both sign and speech as compared to sign or speech alone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Another point of controversy made by advocates are that there are racial disparities in the cochlear implantation evaluation process.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Data taken from 2010-2020 at one academic tertiary care institution showed that 68.5% of patients referred for evaluation were White, 18.5% were Black, and 12.3% were Asian; however the institution's main service area was 46.9% White, 42.3% Black, and 7.7% Asian.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] It was also shown that the Black patients who were referred for evaluation to receive the implants had greater hearing loss compared to White patients who were also referred.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] Based on this study, it is shown that Black patients receive cochlear implants at a disproportionately lower rate than White patients.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] An additional criticism involves the cost of implant upgrades.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] The manufacturers introduce new models on a regular basis and stop servicing older models.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] When this happens, a user who wishes to ensure continued functioning of the implant is required to buy new equipment.
[src:australian-deaf-community/cochlear-implant] This was evident in India for impoverished families whose children received cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] A **contact sign language**, or **contact sign**, is a variety or style of language that arises from contact between deaf individuals using a sign language and hearing individuals using an oral language (or the written or manually coded form of the oral language).
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Contact languages also arise between different sign languages, although the term pidgin rather than contact sign is used to describe such phenomena.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Contact sign has been characterized as "a sign language that has elements of both [a] natural sign language and the surrounding [oral] language".
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Language contact is extremely common in most Deaf communities, which are almost always located within a dominant oral language ('hearing') culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Deaf people are exposed to the oral language that surrounds them, if only in visual forms like lip reading or writing, from early childhood.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Within everyday life it is not uncommon for Deaf people to be in contact with oral languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Hearing parents and teachers of deaf children, if they sign at all, are usually second language learners, and their signing style will exhibit features of interference from the oral language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] A mixing of languages and modes may also occur when interpreting between a spoken and a sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] While deaf sign languages are distinct from spoken languages, with a different vocabulary and grammar, a boundary between the two is often hard to draw.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] A language 'continuum' is often described between signing with a strong sign-language grammar to signing with a strong spoken-language grammar, the middle-regions of which are often described as contact sign (or Pidgin Sign).
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] In a conversation between a native signer and a second-language learner, both conversation partners may be signing at different ends of the spectrum.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] A blend that is often seen is vocabulary from the sign language signed in the word order of the oral language, with a simplified or reduced grammar typical of contact languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] We can recognize that the speaking habits of an English speaker learning French for the first time will differ from those of a native French speaker.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] The same thing happens when a hearing individual is learning a sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] However, even a dialogue between two native deaf signers often shows some evidence of language contact.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Deaf people in the United States may use a more English-like signing style in a more formal setting, or if unfamiliar with the interlocutor.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Sign language researchers Ceil Lucas and Clayton Valli have noted several differences between the language contact arising between two sign languages and the contact phenomena that arise between a signed and an oral language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] When two sign languages meet, the expected contact phenomena occurs: lexical borrowing, foreign "accent", interference, code switching, pidgins, creoles and mixed systems.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Long-term contact with oral languages has generated a large influence on the vocabulary and grammar of sign languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Loan translations are common, such as the American Sign Language signs BOY and FRIEND, forming a compound meaning "boyfriend" or the Auslan partial-calque DON'T MIND, which involves the sign for the noun MIND combined with an upturned palm, which is a typical Auslan negation.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] When a loan translation becomes fully acceptable and considered as 'native' (rather than Contact Signing) is a matter over which native signers will differ in opinion.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] The process appears to be very common in those sign languages that have been best documented, such as American Sign Language, British Sign Language and Auslan.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] In all of the cases, signers are increasingly bilingual in both a sign and a "spoken" language (or visual forms of it) as the deaf signing community's literacy levels increase.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] In such bilingual communities, loan translations are common enough that deeper grammatical structures may also be borrowed from the oral language, which is known as metatypy.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Some populations with a high proportion of deaf people have developed sign languages that are used by both hearing and deaf people in the community, such as Martha's Vineyard Sign Language, Yucatec Maya Sign Language, Adamorobe Sign Language and Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] It is unclear what kind of language contact phenomena, if any, occur in such environments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] One of the most striking contact sign phenomena is fingerspelling in which a writing system is represented with manual signs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] In the sign languages with such a system, the manual alphabet is structurally quite different from the more 'native' grammatical forms, which are often spatial, visually motivated, and multilayered.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Manual alphabets facilitate the input of new terms such as technical vocabulary from the dominant oral language of the region and allow a transliteration of phrases, names, and places.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] They may also be used for function words such as 'at', 'so' or 'but'.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] The phrase Pidgin Sign English (PSE, sometimes also 'Pidgin Signed English') is often used to describe the different contact languages that arise between the English language and any of British Sign Language, New Zealand Sign Language, Auslan or American Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] However, that term is falling out of favour.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Pidgin Signed English generally refers to a combination of American Sign Language and the English language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Individuals who are hard of hearing, or become deaf later on in life, after using Spoken English, may often use a mixture of ASL and English, which is known as PSE.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] With PSE, it is common to sign most English words of a sentence, using English grammar and syntax, using ASL signs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] When communicating with hearing English speakers, ASL-speakers often use PSE.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Various types of PSE exist, ranging from highly English-influenced PSE (practically relexified English) to PSE which is quite close to ASL lexically and grammatically, but may alter some subtle features of ASL grammar.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Fingerspelling may be used more often in PSE than it is normally used in ASL.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Contact phenomena have been observed in the reverse direction, from a sign language to an oral language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/contact-signing] Hearing adults who grew up in deaf signing households as children of deaf adults (CODAs) sometimes communicate with one another in spoken and written English and knowingly use ASL loan translations and underlying grammatical forms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Members of various Deaf communities worldwide tend to view deafness as a difference in human experience rather than a disability or disease.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Many members take pride in their Deaf identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf people, in the sense of a community or culture, can then be seen as a linguistic minority, and therefore some who are a part of this community may feel misunderstood by those who do not know sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Another struggle that the Deaf community often faces is that educational institutions usually consist primarily of hearing people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Additionally, hearing family members may need to learn sign language in order for the deaf person to feel included and supported.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Unlike some other cultures, a deaf person may join the community later in life, rather than needing to be born into it.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are several perspectives on deaf people and Deaf culture that shape their treatment and role in society.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] From a medical standpoint, many encourage Deaf children to undergo surgery.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In the past, the medical perspective discouraged the use of sign language because they believed it will detract from the development of auditory and speech skills.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Although this assumption has since been disproven (the use of sign language has been discovered to play a crucial role in the acquisition of these skills), many audiologists and doctors mistakenly believe it to be true.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] From a social standpoint, Deaf individuals are welcomed to participate in society in the same manner as any other individual.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This view discourages the idea that those who are deaf or hard-of-hearing are sick and in need of a cure.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The social view also encourages making accommodations for deaf people so that they can fully participate in society.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Such accommodations include the use of interpreters or improved closed captioning systems.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Some feel the social view fails to recognize the unique qualities of Deaf people and Deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] They believe that this perspective asks Deaf people to fit and find their own way in a predominantly hearing society, instead of recognizing their own abilities and culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Another perspective is referred to as the cultural-linguistic view.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Supporters of Deaf Culture state that this perspective appropriately recognizes Deaf people as a minority culture in the world with their own language and social norms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This standpoint is believed to promote Deaf people's right to collective space within society to pass on their language and culture to future generations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Being involved in the Deaf community and culturally identifying as Deaf has been shown to significantly contribute to positive self-esteem in Deaf individuals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The community can provide support, easy social interaction, and "refuge from the grinding frustrations of the hearing world." Conversely, deaf individuals who are not a part of the Deaf community may not have the same support in the hearing world, resulting in lower self-esteem.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Stereotypes, lack of knowledge, and negative attitudes about Deafness cause widespread discrimination.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This could lead to a lower education and economic status for deaf people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The community may include hearing family members of deaf people and sign-language interpreters who identify with Deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] It does not automatically include all people who are deaf or hard-of-hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] They enhance their nations in areas of education, economic activity, politics, arts and literature.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In Deaf culture, "sumain" refers to people who communicate with each other using their hands.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Marla Berkowitz, a Certified Deaf ASL interpreter, describes it as "a coined word from two languages – Su – your; main – hands".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Historically, acculturation has often occurred within schools for Deaf students and within Deaf social clubs, both of which unite deaf people into communities with which they can identify.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Becoming Deaf culturally can occur at different times for different people, depending on the circumstances of one's life.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] A small proportion of deaf individuals acquire sign language and Deaf culture in infancy from Deaf parents, others acquire it through attendance at schools, and yet others may not be exposed to sign language and Deaf culture until college or a time after that.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Although up to fifty percent of deafness has genetic causes, fewer than five percent of deaf people have a deaf parent, so Deaf communities are unusual among cultural groups in that most members do not acquire their cultural identities from parents.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Educator and ASL interpreter Anna Mindess notes that there is "not just one homogeneous deaf culture".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are many distinct Deaf communities around the world, which communicate using different sign languages and exhibit different cultural norms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf identity also intersects with other kinds of cultural identity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf culture intersects with nationality, education, race, ethnicity, gender, class, sexual orientation, and other identity markers, leading to a culture that is at once quite small and also tremendously diverse.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The extent to which people identify primarily with their deaf identity rather than their membership in other intersecting cultural groups also varies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Aramburo found in a study titled *The Sociolinguistic Aspects of the Black Deaf Community* (1989) that "87 percent of black deaf people polled identified with their black culture first".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf youth who belong to multiple minority groups face exceptional challenges.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf Black individuals may encounter discrimination from both hearing people of the Black community and White Deaf individuals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Though racism is not greater than audism, the intersection of race and deafness (and other identities) can increase the barriers to success and compound hardship.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Therefore, it is crucial to acknowledge the intersectionality of Black Deaf students as it plays a significant role in their educational success.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In his central work on Deafhood, English scholar Pady Ladd often emphasizes a strong sense of collectivity within the Deaf community, but also correctly points out that other forms of marginalization also exist within this community, e.g. towards Deaf people from other countries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Racial discrimination is also noted: Deaf schools in the USA did not admit black students for a long time.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The examples mentioned by Ladd also point to tendencies towards gender discrimination.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] He also points out that his analyses focus strongly on the USA and the UK, and that the situation and self-definition of d/Deaf people in other countries can differ greatly.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Like other authors, however, he assumes a common core of a Deaf culture that arises from experiences as a Deaf person(s).
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Research in Tanzania in the early 21st century resulted in differing analysis whether or not - or how much - the identify of deaf Tanzanians can be characterized as Deaf, pointing also to intersectional identities.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf culture is prevalent in K–12 schools for the deaf throughout the world, though higher education specifically for them is more limited.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Abbé Charles-Michel de l'Épée opened the first school for the deaf in Paris called the Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris (English: *National Institute for Deaf Children of Paris)* in 1760.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] American Sign Language (ASL) started to evolve from primarily French Sign Language (LSF), and other outside influences.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In a residential school where all the children use the same communication system (whether it is a school using sign language, Total Communication or Oralism), students will be able to interact "normally" with other students, without having to worry about being criticized.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] An argument supporting inclusion, on the other hand, exposes the student to people who are not just like them, preparing them for adult life.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Through interacting, children with hearing disabilities can expose themselves to other cultures which in the future may be beneficial for them when it comes to finding jobs and living on their own in a society where their disability may put them in the minority.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] These are some reasons why a person may or may not want to put their child in an inclusion classroom.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In comparison to the general public, deaf people have lower levels of educational achievement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Advocates in deaf education believe that an improved recognition of American Sign Language (ASL) as an official language would improve education, as well as economic status.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Some argue that by improving the recognition of ASL, better access to school materials, deaf teachers, interpreters, and video-telephone communication would take place.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Gallaudet University is the first and only liberal-arts college for deaf students in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Those who are deaf (by either state or federal standards) have access to a free and appropriate public education.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] If a child does qualify as being deaf or hard of hearing and receives an individualized education plan, the IEP team must consider "the child's language and communication needs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The IEP must include opportunities for direct communication with peers and professionals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Department of Education defines deafness as "a hearing impairment that is so severe that the child is impaired in processing linguistic information through hearing, with or without amplification".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Hearing impairment is defined as "an impairment in hearing, whether permanent or fluctuating, that adversely affects a child's educational performance but that is not included under the definition of deafness".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf culture is an active and vital aspect of deaf communities in many countries other than the U.S. and Europe.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Brazil has several institutions, including Instituto Santa Tersinha and Escola para Crianças Surdas Rio Branco.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] China's deaf universities include Beijing Union University, Special Education College of Beijing University, and Zhengzhou University.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Other notable universities for the deaf across the globe include Finland School for the Deaf in Finland, Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris in France, and Berlin School for the Deaf in Germany.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Sign language is just one part of deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf identity is also constructed around specific beliefs, values and art.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Members of Deaf cultures communicate via sign languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Sign languages convey meaning through manual communication and body language instead of acoustically conveyed sound patterns.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This involves the simultaneous combination of hand shapes, orientation and movement of the hands, arms or body, and facial expressions to express a speaker's thoughts.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] "Sign languages are based on the idea that vision is the most useful tool a deaf person has to communicate and receive information".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are over 200 distinct sign languages in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] These include 114 sign languages listed in the Ethnologue database and 157 more sign languages, systems, and dialects.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] While the United Kingdom and the United States are both predominantly English speaking, the predominant signed languages used in these countries differ markedly.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Due to the origins of deaf education in the United States, American Sign Language is most closely related to French Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] A cochlear implant is not to be mistaken for a hearing aid, which makes noises and sounds louder for the user to hear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Instead, cochlear implants bypass the outer ear and target the inner ear where the auditory nerve fibers are stimulated.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] To do this, noises and sounds are transformed into electrical energy which is translated as audio information by the nerve which is then sent to the brain.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] An external microphone captures outside sound, a transmitter processes these sounds and sends them to a receiver embedded under the skin in the skull, and the receiver transforms these sounds into electrical impulses which stimulate the auditory nerve.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The medical model of disability can be aligned with technological advancements in cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This is due to the fact that cochlear implants can be perceived to "cure" deafness or fix an individual's hearing, when in reality those who are Deaf may not feel a need to be cured or fixed.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This idea is seen in many children's books, where improved quality of life is only seen after characters obtain cochlear implants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This idea that deafness is a physiological issue that resides only within the individual and therefore should be physiologically fixed or solved counters the teachings and beliefs within Deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Often people feel as though children should make the decision if they want a cochlear implant for themselves as opposed to someone else, like their parents or caregivers, making it for them.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Although ethical, this idea poses a problem since the success rate of cochlear implants is at its highest when implanted at early childhood; in other words, when the child is not able to make rather large decisions, like this one, for themselves.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] These critics argue forcing cochlear implants on children should be reduced and the assumption that cochlear implants offer the best quality of life for Deaf individuals should be countered.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] One way of doing this would be to expose children of young ages to Deaf culture and the Deaf community early on, as well as teach them American Sign Language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Cochlear implants have been controversial around the Deaf community ever since they first were made available to the public.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Those who oppose cochlear implants even refer to it as "cultural genocide," as it lessens the prevalence and importance of Deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] People are against cochlear implants for a variety of reasons, including: there is value to being Deaf, being Deaf is not an illness and does not require a cure, the Deaf are not lesser than the hearing, etc.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Cochlear implants also have a variety of risks associated with them, like costliness, effectiveness, and surgical requirement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Alternatively, those who support cochlear implants do not necessarily oppose Deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Culture itself is not a simple concept, but rather it has high levels of complexity and power; due to this nature, culture is not to be applied narrowly to a group of individuals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The Deaf community is composed of highly diverse Deaf individuals, and to impose narrow culture onto a group full of heterogeneous members would be rather questionable.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There is room for deviation and hybridization of values and beliefs in Deaf culture as society and technology evolves.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Even if they are proud of their Deaf identity, many deaf individuals wish they knew what their voices sounded like, and wish they could pick up the phone and have a conversation with ease without the need for a third-party device or interpreter.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] So, instead of looking at cochlear implants as identity stripping, many Deaf parents of Deaf children see cochlear implants as a way to give their children more than what they have; to offer them the pleasure of being able to hear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] It has also been proven that cochlear implants help to provide opportunities for success, and help individuals to feel more connected to the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Though most Deaf individuals agree that choosing to use a cochlear implant is a difficult decision, many say that resistance to cochlear implants has decreased since 1990, the year when it was first approved for children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] By building more evidence of the benefits and limitations of cochlear implants, both Deaf and hearing individuals can be properly educated on the impact of cochlear implants, and thus unrealistic expectations and controversies can be resolved.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] A strong tradition of poetry and storytelling exists in American Sign Language and other sign languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Some prominent performers in the United States include Clayton Valli, Ben Bahan, Ella Mae Lentz, Manny Hernandez, CJ Jones, Debbie Rennie, Patrick Graybill, Peter Cook, and many others.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Their works are now increasingly available on video.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Culturally Deaf people have also represented themselves in the dominant written languages of their nations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Miller and Chuck Baird have produced visual artwork that conveys a Deaf worldview.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Douglas Tilden was a famous Deaf sculptor who produced many different sculptures in his lifetime.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Some Deaf artists belong to an art movement called De'VIA, which stands for Deaf View Image Art.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Organizations such as the Deaf Professional Arts Network or D-PAN are dedicated to promoting professional development and access to the entertainment, visual and media arts fields for individuals who are deaf or hard-of-hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Daily Moth was established by Alex Abenchuchan in 2017 to make the news accessible for Deaf ASL users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In the United States, the Cobbs School, a deaf school in Virginia, was established in 1815.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This school lasted only one and half years due to financial setbacks.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] American Deaf Community recounts the story of Laurent Clerc, a deaf educator, coming to the United States from France in 1817 to help found the first permanent school for deaf children in the country now named American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] American School is the first official school for the deaf.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Another well-known event is the 1880 Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf in Milan, Italy, where hearing educators voted to embrace oral education and remove sign language from the classroom.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This effort resulted in pressure around the world to abandon sign language in favor of the oral approach exclusively.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The intent of the oralist method was to teach deaf children to speak and lip read with limited or no use of sign language in the classroom in order to make it easier for deaf children to integrate into hearing communities, but the benefits of learning in such an environment are disputed.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The Milan conference recommendations were repudiated in Hamburg a century later, and sign languages in education came back into vogue after the publication of Stokoe's linguistic analyses of ASL.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf clubs, popular in the 1940s and 1950s, were also an important part of deaf culture.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] During this time there were very few places that deaf people could call their own– places run by deaf people for deaf people.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Films were made from the Los Angeles Club for the Deaf and included styles of performances such as Vaudeville show and short comedy skills.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Wolf Bragg, a popular Deaf club performer through 1930 is known for interpreting sign language into "The Monkey's Paw" and "Auf Wiedersehen".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf clubs were the solution to this need.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Money was made by selling alcohol and hosting card games.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Sometimes these ventures were so successful that the building used by the club was able to be purchased.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The main attraction of these clubs was that they provided a place that deaf people could go to be around other deaf people, sometimes sharing stories, hosting parties, comedians, and plays.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Many of today's common ABC stories were first seen at deaf clubs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The clubs were found in all of the major cities, New York City being home to at least 12.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] These clubs were an important break from their usually solitary day spent at factory jobs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In the 1960s, deaf clubs began their quick and drastic decline.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Today there are only a few spread-out deaf clubs found in the United States and their attendance is commonly small with a tendency to the elderly.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This sudden decline is often attributed to the rise of technology like the TTY and closed captioning for personal TVs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] With other options available for entertainment and communication, the need for deaf clubs grew smaller.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] It was no longer the only option for getting in touch with other members of the deaf community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Others attribute the decline of deaf clubs to the end of World War II and a change in the job market.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] During WWII there was high demand for factory laborers and a promise of high pay.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Many deaf Americans left their homes to move to bigger cities with the hope of obtaining a factory job.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This huge influx of workers into new cities created the need for deaf clubs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] When World War II ended and the civil rights movement progressed, the federal government started offering more jobs to deaf men and women.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] People began switching from manufacturing jobs to service jobs, moving away from solitary work with set hours.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Today, deaf clubs are rare, but deaf advocacy centers and other deaf organizations have become widespread and popular.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 1986, Baltimore Leather Association of the Deaf (BLADeaf), the first deaf leather club in America, was founded.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Its original name was Maryland Lambda Alliance of the Deaf and it had three name changes before its name was changed to BLADeaf.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Bennett, Scott Wilson, and Harry "Abbe" Woosley Jr.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] According to BLADeaf, the fact of the Baltimore Eagle being BLADeaf's home bar means the Baltimore Eagle is the world's first bar to home a deaf leather organization.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 1989, a deaf chapter of the National Leather Association called “NLA: Deaf Chapter”, which eventually became International Deaf Leather, was founded by Michael Felts, Philip Rubin, Bob Donaldson, Rolf Hagton, Jim Dunne, Bobby Andrascik and Charles Wilkinson.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] International Deaf Leather held contests for the titles International Ms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf Leather, and International Deaf Leather Boy.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] International Deaf Leather ended in 2021.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf leathermen sometimes compete at International Mr.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Leather (IML); in 1992, IML featured three deaf contestants.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are several major institutions supporting the Deaf queer community in the United States.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The Rainbow Alliance of the Deaf (RAD), previously named National Rainbow Society of the Deaf (NRSD), is a nonprofit established in America in 1977 to, "establish and maintain a society of Deaf LGBT".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The RAD hosts an annual conference "to encourage and promote the educational, economical, and social welfare of Deaf LGBTQ individuals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] RAD now has chapters in the United States and Canada.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The Deaf Queer Resource Center (DQRC), was founded in 1995 founded by Drago Renteria and began as a website connects people to resources nationally.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Support and community groups for people with intersectional LGBTQ identities in the Deaf, DeafBlind, DeafDisabled and Hard of Hearing communities using ASL are held regionally and virtually.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Queer ASL is an educational platform taught virtually by Deaf queer instructors focused on educating queer and trans people in a safe space.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Deaf queer events include Rainbow Alliance of the Deaf conferences, the Deaf Lesbian Festival, and Deaf Queer Men Only.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Internationally, institutions include the Hong Kong Bauhinias Deaf Club, Deaf LGBTW in Fukoaka, Tohoku, Tokyo, and Osaka, Pinoy Deaf Rainbow in the Philippines, Deaf Rainbow NSW in Australia, Deaf Rainbow UK, Rainbow International Deaf at Israel, and the Greenbow LGBT Society of Ireland.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are deaf churches (where sign language is the main language), deaf synagogues, deaf Jewish community centers, and the Hebrew Seminary of the Deaf in Illinois.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 2011 the Conservative Movement unanimously passed the rabbinic responsa, "The Status of the Heresh [one who is deaf] and of Sign Language", by the Committee on Jewish Law and Standards (CJLS).
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] This responsa declared that, among other things, "The Committee on Jewish Law and Standards rules that the deaf who communicate via sign language and do not speak are no longer to be considered mentally incapacitated.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Jews who are deaf are responsible for observing mitzvot.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Our communities, synagogues, schools, and camps must strive to be welcoming and accessible, and inclusive.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Sign language may be used in matters of personal status and may be used in rituals.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] A deaf person called to the Torah who does not speak may recite the berakhot via sign language.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] There are 15 chapters of Deaf Women United throughout the United States; its mission is, "to promote the lives of Deaf women through empowerment, enrichment, and networking." There is also Pink Wings of Hope, an American breast cancer support group for deaf and hard-of-hearing women.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The library at Gallaudet University, the only deaf liberal arts university in the United States, was founded in 1876.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The library's collection has grown from a small number of reference books to the world's largest collection of deaf-related materials, with over 234,000 books and thousands of other materials in different formats.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The collection is so large that the library had to create a hybrid classification system based on the Dewey Decimal Classification System in order to make cataloging and location within the library easier for both library staff and users.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The library also houses the university's archives, which holds some of the oldest deaf-related books and documents in the world.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The American Library Association, also founded in 1876, has stated that disabled people belong to a minority that is often overlooked and underrepresented by people in the library, and the Deaf community belongs in this minority group.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The ALA's Library Bill of Rights preamble states that "all libraries are forums for information and ideas" and as such libraries need to remove the physical and technological barriers which in turn would allow persons with disabilities full access to the resources available.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] One notable American activist in the library community working toward accessibility for the deaf was Alice Lougee Hagemeyer, herself deaf.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 1974 she created Deaf Awareness Week, later called Deaf Heritage Week, in which programs about deaf culture are held in libraries.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 1980 she founded the unit now known as the Library Service to People who are Deaf or Hard of Hearing Forum, which is a unit within the American Library Association.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In 2006 the American Library Association and the (American) National Association of the Deaf declared that they would recognize March 13 to April 15 as National Deaf History Month.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] New guidelines from library organizations such as International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions (IFLA) and the ALA were written in order to help libraries make their information more accessible to people with disabilities, and in some cases, specifically the Deaf community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] IFLA's *Guidelines for Library Services to Deaf People* is one such set of guidelines, and it was published to inform libraries of the services that should be provided for Deaf patrons.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Most of the guidelines pertain to ensuring that Deaf patrons have equal access to all available library services.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] Over the years, library services have begun to evolve in order to accommodate the needs and desires of local Deaf communities.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] For example, at the Queens Borough Public Library (QBPL) in New York, the staff implemented new and innovative ideas in order to involve the community and library staff with the Deaf people in their community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The QBPL hired a deaf librarian, Lori Stambler-Dunsmore, to train the library staff about Deaf culture, to teach sign language classes for family members and people who are involved with deaf people, and to teach literacy classes for Deaf patrons.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In working with the library, Stambler-Dunsmore was able to help the community reach out to its deaf neighbors, and helped other deaf people become more active in their outside community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] In Nashville, Tennessee, Sandy Cohen manages the Library Services for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (LSDHH).
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf-community] The program was created in 1979 in response to information accessibility issues for the Deaf in the Nashville area.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In a medical context, deafness is defined as a degree of hearing difficulties such that a person is unable to understand speech, even in the presence of amplification.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In profound deafness, even the loudest sounds produced by an audiometer (an instrument used to measure hearing by producing pure tone sounds through a range of frequencies) may not be perceived by the person.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In total deafness, no sounds at all, regardless of amplification or method of production, can be heard.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Neurologically, language is processed in the same brain areas whether one is deaf or hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The left hemisphere of the brain processes linguistic patterns whether by signed languages or by spoken languages.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] All of these forms of hearing loss impair a person's hearing; they are unable to perceive or interpret sounds correctly.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] These different types of hearing loss occur in different parts of the ear, which makes it difficult for the information heard to reach the brain properly.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] For each of these types, there are four different levels or amounts of hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] This is when someone can still hear noises, but it is more difficult to hear the softer sounds.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The second level is *moderate hearing loss*, and this is when someone can hear almost nothing when someone is talking to them at a normal volume.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] *Severe hearing loss* is when someone can not hear any sounds when they are being produced at a normal level, and they can only hear minimal sounds that are being produced at a loud level.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The final level is *profound hearing loss*, which is when someone is not able to hear any sounds except for very loud ones.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Millions of people globally live with deafness or hearing impairments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The 2005 Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP) indicated that fewer than 1 in 20 Americans are deaf or hard of hearing (DHH) at a level that makes normal conversations difficult to hear; more than half of these people are over retirement age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Several solutions are available for many people with hearing impairments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Additionally, people may use devices that use blinking lights instead of noises for alarm clocks or other notifications.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Cochlear implants are an option for children and adults with severe or profound hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Cochlear implants are surgically placed devices that stimulate the cochlear nerve to help the person hear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] A cochlear implant is used instead of hearing aids to help when someone has difficulties understanding speech.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] For children, the younger they are at the time of implantation, the better their auditory skill and perception.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Babies with confirmed bilateral profound sensorineural hearing loss may begin the surgical evaluation process for implantation as early as six months, with the US officially allowing the surgery to take place as early as nine months of age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Children with other medical problems or other types of hearing loss may be considered at a slightly older age.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Parents sometimes have difficulty deciding to get cochlear implants for their child.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Many felt a sense of urgency, and, in the end, most parents felt it was beneficial for their child.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In a cultural context, Deaf culture refers to a tight-knit cultural group of people whose primary language is signed, and who practice social and cultural norms which are distinct from those of the surrounding hearing community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] This community does not automatically include all those who are clinically or legally deaf, nor does it exclude every hearing person.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] According to Baker and Padden, it includes any person who "identifies him/herself as a member of the Deaf community, and other members accept that person as a part of the community", an example being children of deaf adults with normal hearing ability.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] It includes the set of social beliefs, behaviors, art, literary traditions, history, values, and shared institutions of communities influenced by deafness and use sign languages as the main means of communication.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] While deafness is often included within the umbrella of disability, members of the Deaf community tend to view deafness as a difference in human experience or as a language minority.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Many non-disabled people incorrectly assume that deaf people have no autonomy.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] As children, deaf people learn literacy differently from hearing children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] They learn to speak and write, whereas hearing children naturally learn to speak and eventually learn to write.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The Quota International organization, headquartered in the United States, provided considerable educational support in the Philippines, where it began offering free education to deaf children in the Leganes Resource Center for the Deaf.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The British organisation Sounds Seekers also supported deaf communities by offering audiology maintenance technology in hard-to-reach areas.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The Nippon Foundation supports deaf students at Gallaudet University and the National Technical Institute for the Deaf through international scholarship programs to encourage them to become future leaders in the deaf community.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] These organizations hope to provide opportunities and resources for the deaf community, and hope that they can help society build a more inclusive and tolerant environment for future generations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The first known record of sign language in history comes from Plato's Cratylus, written in the fifth century BCE.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In 1760, French philanthropic educator Charles-Michel de l'Épée opened the world's first free school for the deaf.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The school won approval for government funding in 1791 and became known as the "Institution Nationale des Sourds-Muets à Paris".
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Parents of deaf and hard-of-hearing children often encounter difficulties when choosing an educational setting for their child.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] They may consider the child's needs and abilities, how the school can accommodate the child, and the school environment itself.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] Both the child and the parent may benefit from trial and error with different schools, to identify the best available environment.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] There are two major paths available to deaf students.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] One option is to attend a public, non-specialized school, the same as they would if they were hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] If the student is mainstreamed, they may use an interpreter in class, wear hearing aids, or other accommodations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] The second option is to attend a specialized Deaf school.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] In America, most states have at least one.
[src:australian-deaf-community/deaf] These are often boarding schools, and students will come from all over the state to attend.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A **hearing aid** is a device designed to improve hearing by making sound audible to a person with hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aids are classified as medical devices in most countries, and regulated by the respective regulations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Small audio amplifiers such as personal sound amplification products (PSAPs) or other plain sound reinforcing systems cannot be sold as "hearing aids".
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Early devices, such as ear trumpets or ear horns, were passive amplification cones designed to gather sound energy and direct it into the ear canal.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Modern devices are computerised electroacoustic systems that transform environmental sound to make it audible, according to audiometrical and cognitive rules.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Modern devices also utilize sophisticated digital signal processing, aiming to improve speech intelligibility and comfort for the user.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Such signal processing includes feedback management, wide dynamic range compression, directionality, frequency lowering, and noise reduction.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Modern hearing aids require calibration and configuration to match the hearing loss, physical features, and lifestyle of the wearer.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The hearing aid is fitted to the most recent audiogram and is programmed by frequency.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This process, called "fitting", can be performed by the user in simple cases, by a Doctor of Audiology (an AuD) - also called an audiologist, or by a Hearing Instrument Specialist (HIS) or audioprosthologist.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The amount of benefits a hearing aid delivers depends in large part on the quality of its fitting.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Almost all hearing aids in use in the United States are digital hearing aids, as analog aids are phased out.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Devices similar to hearing aids include the osseointegrated auditory prosthesis (formerly called the bone-anchored hearing aid) and cochlear implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aids are used for a variety of pathologies including sensorineural hearing loss, conductive hearing loss, and single-sided deafness.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aid candidacy was traditionally determined by a Doctor of Audiology, or a certified hearing specialist, who will also fit the device based on the nature and degree of the hearing loss being treated.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The amount of benefit experienced by the user of the hearing aid is multi-factorial, depending on the type, severity, and etiology of the hearing loss, the technology and fitting of the device, and on the motivation, personality, lifestyle, and overall health of the user.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Over-the-counter hearing aids, which address mild to moderate hearing loss, are designed to be adjusted by the user.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aids are incapable of truly correcting a hearing loss; they are an *aid* to make sounds more audible.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The most common form of hearing loss for which hearing aids are sought is sensorineural, resulting from damage to the hair cells and synapses of the cochlea and auditory nerve.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Sensorineural hearing loss reduces the sensitivity to sound, which a hearing aid can partially accommodate by making sound louder.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Conductive hearing losses, which do not involve damage to the cochlea, tend to be better treated by hearing aids; the hearing aid is able to sufficiently amplify sound to account for the attenuation caused by the conductive component.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Once the sound is able to reach the cochlea at normal or near-normal levels, the cochlea and auditory nerve are able to transmit signals to the brain normally.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Common issues with hearing aid fitting and use are the occlusion effect, loudness recruitment, and understanding speech in noise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Once a common problem, feedback is generally now well-controlled through the use of feedback management algorithms.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] There are many ways to evaluate how well a hearing aid compensates for hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] One approach is audiometry which measures a subject's hearing levels in laboratory conditions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The threshold of audibility for various sounds and intensities is measured in a variety of conditions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Although audiometric tests may attempt to mimic real-world conditions, the patient's own every day experiences may differ.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] An alternative approach is self-report assessment, where the patient reports their experience with the hearing aid.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The most reliable method for assessing the correct adjustment of a hearing aid is through real ear measurement.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Real ear measurements (or probe microphone measurements) are an assessment of the characteristics of hearing aid amplification near the ear drum using a silicone probe tube microphone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] There are many types of hearing aids (also known as hearing instruments), which vary in size, power and circuitry.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Body worn aids were the first portable electronic hearing aids, and were invented by Harvey Fletcher while working at Bell Laboratories.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Body aids consist of a case and an earmold, attached by a wire.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The case contains the electronic amplifier components, controls and battery, while the earmold typically contains a miniature loudspeaker.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The case is typically about the size of a pack of playing cards and is carried in a pocket or on a belt.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Without the size constraints of smaller hearing devices, body worn aid designs can provide large amplification and long battery life at a lower cost.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Body aids are still used in emerging markets because of their relatively low cost.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Behind the ear hearing aids are one of two major classes of hearing aids – behind the ear (BTE) and in the ear (ITE).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These two classes are distinguished by where the hearing aid is worn.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTE hearing aids consist of a case which hangs behind the pinna.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The case is attached to an earmold or dome tip by a traditional tube, slim tube, or wire.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The tube or wire courses from the superior-ventral portion of the pinna to the concha, where the ear mold or dome tip inserts into the external auditory canal.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The case contains the electronics, controls, battery, and microphone(s).The loudspeaker, or receiver, may be housed in the case (traditional BTE) or in the earmold or dome tip (receiver-in-the-canal, or RIC).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The RIC style of BTE hearing aid is often smaller than a traditional BTE and more commonly used in more active populations.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTEs are generally capable of providing more output and may therefore be indicated for more severe degrees of hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] However, BTEs are very versatile and can be used for nearly any kind of hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTEs come in a variety of sizes, ranging from a small, "mini BTE", to larger, ultra-power devices.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Size typically depends on the output level needed, the location of the receiver, and the presence or absence of a telecoil.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTEs are durable, easy to repair, and often have controls and battery doors that are easier to manipulate.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTEs are also easily connected to assistive listening devices, such as FM systems and induction loops.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] BTEs are commonly worn by children who need a durable type of hearing aid.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] In the ear aids (ITE) devices fit in the outer ear bowl (called the concha).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Being larger, these are easier to insert and can hold extra features.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] They are sometimes visible when standing face to face with someone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] ITE hearing aids are custom made to fit each individual's ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] They can be used in mild to some severe hearing losses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Feedback, a squealing/whistling caused by sound (particularly high frequency sound) leaking and being amplified again, may be a problem for severe hearing losses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Some modern circuits are able to provide feedback regulation or cancellation to assist with this.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A vent is a tube primarily placed to offer pressure equalization.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] However, different vent styles and sizes can be used to influence and prevent feedback.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Traditionally, ITEs have not been recommended for young children because their fit could not be as easily modified as the earmold for a BTE, and thus the aid had to be replaced frequently as the child grew.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] However, there are new ITEs made from a silicone type material that mitigates the need for costly replacements.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] ITE hearing aids can be connected wirelessly to FM systems, for instance with a body-worn FM receiver with induction neck-loop which transmits the audio signal from the FM transmitter inductively to the telecoil inside the hearing instrument.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Mini in canal (MIC) or completely in canal (CIC) aids are generally not visible unless the viewer looks directly into the wearer's ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These aids are intended for mild to moderately severe losses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] CICs are usually not recommended for people with good low-frequency hearing, as the occlusion effect is much more noticeable.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Completely-in-the-canal hearing aids fit tightly deep in the ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Being small, it will not have a directional microphone, and its small batteries will have a short life, and the batteries and controls may be difficult to manage.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Its position in the ear prevents wind noise and makes it easier to use phones without feedback.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] In-the-canal hearing aids are placed deep in the ear canal.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Larger versions of these can have directional microphones.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Being in the canal, they are less likely to cause a plugged feeling.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These models are easier to manipulate than the smaller completely in-the-canal models but still have the drawbacks of being rather small.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] In-the-ear hearing aids are typically more expensive than behind-the-ear counterparts of equal functionality, because they are custom fitted to the patient's ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] In fitting, the audiologist takes a physical impression (mold) of the ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The mold is scanned by a specialized CAD system, resulting in a 3D model of the outer ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] During modeling, the venting tube is inserted.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The digitally modeled *shell* is printed using a rapid prototyping technique such as stereolithography.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Finally, the aid is assembled and shipped to the audiologist after a quality check.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Invisible-in-canal hearing aids (IIC) style of hearing aids fits inside the ear canal completely, leaving little to no trace of an installed hearing aid visible.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This is because it fits deeper in the canal than other types, so that it is out of view even when looking directly into the ear bowl (concha).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A comfortable fit is achieved because the shell of the aid is custom-made to the individual ear canal after taking a mold.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Invisible hearing aid types use venting and their deep placement in the ear canal to give a more natural experience of hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Unlike other hearing aid types, with the IIC aid the majority of the ear is not blocked (occluded) by a large plastic shell.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This means that sound can be collected more naturally by the shape of the ear, and can travel down into the ear canal as it would with unassisted hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Depending on their size, some models allow the wearer to use a mobile phone as a remote control to alter memory and volume settings, instead of taking the IIC out to do this.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] IIC types are most suitable for users up to middle age, but are not suitable for elderly people with unsteady hands.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Extended wear hearing aids are hearing devices that are non-surgically placed in the ear canal by a hearing professional.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The extended wear hearing aid represents the first "invisible" hearing device.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These devices are worn for 1–3 months at a time without removal.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] They are made of soft material designed to contour to each user and can be used by people with mild to moderately severe hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Their close proximity to the ear drum results in improved sound directionality and localization, reduced feedback, and improved high frequency gain.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] While traditional BTE or ITC hearing aids require daily insertion and removal, extended wear hearing aids are worn continuously and then replaced with a new device.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Users can change volume and settings without the aid of a hearing professional.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The devices are very useful for active individuals because their design protects against moisture and earwax and can be worn while exercising, showering, etc.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Because the device's placement within the ear canal makes them invisible to observers, extended wear hearing aids are popular with those who are self-conscious about the aesthetics of BTE or ITC hearing aid models.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] As with other hearing devices, compatibility is based on an individual's hearing loss, ear size and shape, medical conditions, and lifestyle.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The disadvantages include regular removal and reinsertion of the device when the battery dies, inability to go underwater, earplugs when showering, and for some discomfort with the fit since it is inserted deeply in the ear canal, the only part of the body where skin rests directly on top of bone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A CROS hearing aid is a hearing aid that transmits auditory information from one side of the head to the other side of the head.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Candidates include people who have poor word understanding on one side, no hearing on one side, or who are not benefiting from a hearing aid on one side.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] CROS hearing aids can appear very similar to behind the ear hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The CROS system can assist the patient in sound localization and understanding auditory information on their poor side.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] While CROS hearing aids can be quite effective, the long-term solution for those with hearing issues on one side is to use a BiCROS system.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This creates more of a balance for wearers.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A bone anchored hearing aid (BAHA) is a surgically implanted auditory prosthetic based on bone conduction.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] It is an option for patients without external ear canals, when conventional hearing aids with a mold in the ear cannot be used.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The BAHA uses the skull as a pathway for sound to travel to the inner ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] For people with conductive hearing loss, the BAHA bypasses the external auditory canal and middle ear, stimulating the functioning cochlea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] For people with unilateral hearing loss, the BAHA uses the skull to conduct the sound from the deaf side to the side with the functioning cochlea.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Individuals under the age of two (five in the USA) typically wear the BAHA device on a Softband.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This can be worn from the age of one month as babies tend to tolerate this arrangement very well.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] When the child's skull bone is sufficiently thick, a titanium "post" can be surgically embedded into the skull with a small abutment exposed outside the skin.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The BAHA sound processor sits on this abutment and transmits sound vibrations to the external abutment of the titanium implant.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The implant vibrates the skull and inner ear, which stimulate the nerve fibers of the inner ear, allowing hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The surgical procedure is simple both for the surgeon, involving very few risks for the experienced ear surgeon.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] For the patient, minimal discomfort and pain is reported.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Patients may experience numbness of the area around the implant as small superficial nerves in the skin are sectioned during the procedure.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] There is no risk of further hearing loss due to the surgery.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] One important feature of the BAHA is that, if a patient for whatever reason does not want to continue with the arrangement, it takes the surgeon less than a minute to remove it.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The BAHA does not restrict the wearer from any activities such as outdoor life, sporting activities etc.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] A BAHA can be connected to an FM system by attaching a miniaturized FM receiver to it.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Two main brands manufacture BAHAs today – the original inventors Cochlear, and the hearing aid company Oticon.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] During the late 1950s to 1970s, before in-the-ear aids became common (and in an era when thick-rimmed eyeglasses were popular), people who wore both glasses and hearing aids frequently chose a type of hearing aid that was built into the temple pieces of the spectacles.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] However, the combination of glasses and hearing aids was inflexible: the range of frame styles was limited, and the user had to wear both hearing aids and glasses at once or wear neither.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Today, people who use both glasses and hearing aids can use in-the-ear types, or rest a BTE neatly alongside the arm of the glasses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] There are still some specialized situations where hearing aids built into the frame of eyeglasses can be useful, such as when a person has hearing loss mainly in one ear: sound from a microphone on the "bad" side can be sent through the frame to the side with better hearing.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This can also be achieved by using CROS or bi-CROS style hearing aids, which are now wireless in sending sound to the better side.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Spectacle aids come in two forms, *bone conduction spectacles* and *air conduction spectacles*.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Sounds are transmitted via a receiver attached from the arm of the spectacles which are fitted firmly behind the boney portion of the skull at the back of the ear, (mastoid process) by means of pressure, applied on the arm of the spectacles.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The sound is passed from the receiver on the arm of the spectacles to the inner ear (cochlea), via the bony portion.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The process of transmitting the sound through the bone requires a great amount of power.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Bone conduction aids generally have a poorer high pitch response and are therefore best used for *conductive hearing losses* or where it is impractical to fit standard hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Unlike the bone conduction spectacles the sound is transmitted via hearing aids which are attached to the arm or arms of the spectacles.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] When removing your glasses for cleaning, the hearing aids are detached at the same time.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Whilst there are genuine instances where spectacle aids are a preferred choice, they may not always be the most practical option.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These 'hearing glasses' incorporate a directional microphone capability: four microphones on each side of the frame effectively work as two directional microphones, which are able to discern between sound coming from the front and sound coming from the sides or back of the user.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] This improves the signal-to-noise ratio by allowing for amplification of the sound coming from the front, the direction in which the user is looking, and active noise control for sounds coming from the sides or behind.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Only very recently has the technology required become small enough to be fitted in the frame of the glasses.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] As a recent addition to the market, this new hearing aid is currently available only in the Netherlands and Belgium.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] These hearing aids are designed for medical practitioners with hearing loss who use stethoscopes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The hearing aid is built into the speaker of the stethoscope, which amplifies the sound.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aid applications (HAA) are software which, when installed on mobile computational platforms, transforms them into hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The principle of HAA operation corresponds to the basic principles of operation of traditional hearing aids: the microphone receives an acoustic signal and converts it into a digital form.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Sound amplification is achieved by the means of a mobile computational platform, in accordance with the degree and type of the user's hearing loss.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The processed audio signal is transformed into an audio signal and output to the user into the headphones/headset.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Signal processing is implemented in real time.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Constructional features of mobile computational platforms imply preferred use of stereo headsets with two speakers, which allows carrying out binaural hearing correction for the left and right ear separately.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] HAAs can work with both wired and wireless headsets and headphones.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] As a rule, HAAs have two operation modes: setup mode and hearing aid mode.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Setup mode involves the user passing an in situ-audiometry procedure, which determines the user's hearing characteristics.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] Hearing aid mode is a hearing correction system that corrects the user's hearing in accordance with the user's hearing thresholds.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] HAAs also incorporate background noise suppression and acoustic feedback suppression.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p01] The user can independently choose a formula to enhance the sound, as well as adjust the level of the desired amplification to their wishes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The first electrical hearing aid used the carbon microphone of the telephone and was introduced in 1896.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The vacuum tube made electronic amplification possible, but early versions of amplified hearing aids were too heavy to carry around.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Miniaturization of vacuum tubes lead to portable models, and after World War II, wearable models using miniature tubes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The transistor invented in 1948 was well suited to the hearing aid application due to low power and small size; hearing aids were an early adopter of transistors.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The development of integrated circuits allowed further improvement of the capabilities of wearable aids, including implementation of digital signal processing techniques and programmability for the individual user's needs.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] A hearing aid and a telephone are "compatible" when they can connect to each other in a way that produces clear, easily understood sound.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The term "compatibility" is applied to all three types of telephones (wired, cordless, and mobile).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Note that telecoil coupling has nothing to do with the radio signal in a cellular or cordless phone: the audio signal picked up by the telecoil is the weak electromagnetic field that is generated by the voice coil in the phone's speaker as it pushes the speaker cone back and forth.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The electromagnetic (telecoil) mode is usually more effective than the acoustic method.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] This is mainly because the microphone is often automatically switched off when the hearing aid is operating in telecoil mode, so background noise is not amplified.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Since there is an electronic connection to the phone, the sound is clearer and distortion is less likely.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] But in order for this to work, the phone has to be hearing-aid compatible.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] More technically, the phone's speaker has to have a voice coil that generates a relatively strong electromagnetic field.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Speakers with strong voice coils are more expensive and require more energy than the tiny ones used in many modern telephones; phones with the small low-power speakers cannot couple electromagnetically with the telecoil in the hearing aid, so the hearing aid must then switch to acoustic mode.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Also, many mobile phones emit high levels of electromagnetic noise that creates audible static in the hearing aid when the telecoil is used.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] A workaround that resolves this issue on many mobile phones is to plug a wired (not Bluetooth) headset into the mobile phone; with the headset placed near the hearing aid the phone can be held far enough away to attenuate the static.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Another method is to use a "neckloop" (which is like a portable, around-the-neck induction loop), and plug the neckloop directly into the standard audio jack (headphones jack) of a smartphone (or laptop, or stereo, etc.).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Then, with the hearing aids' telecoil turned on (usually a button to press), the sound will travel directly from the phone, through the neckloop and into the hearing aids' telecoils.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] On 21 March 2007, the Telecommunications Industry Association issued the TIA-1083 standard, which gives manufacturers of cordless telephones the ability to test their products for compatibility with most hearing aids that have a T-Coil magnetic coupling mode.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] With this testing, digital cordless phone manufacturers will be able to inform consumers about which products will work with their hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The best possible rating is M4/T4 meaning that the phone works well in both modes.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Devices rated below M3 are unsatisfactory for people with hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Computer programs that allow the creation of a hearing aid using a PC, tablet or smartphone are currently gaining in popularity.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Modern mobile devices have all the necessary components to implement this: hardware (an ordinary microphone and headphones may be used) and a high-performance microprocessor that carries digital sound processing according to a given algorithm.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Application configuration is carried out by the user themselves in accordance with the individual features of their hearing ability.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The computational power of modern mobile devices is sufficient to produce the best sound quality.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] This, coupled with software application settings (for example, profile selection according to a sound environment) provides for high comfort and convenience of use.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Functionality of hearing aid applications may involve a hearing test (in situ audiometry) too.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] However, the results of the test are used only to adjust the device for comfortable working with the application.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The procedure of hearing testing in any way cannot claim to replace an audiometry test carried out by a medical specialist, so cannot be a basis for diagnosis.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Recent hearing aids include wireless hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] One hearing aid can transmit to the other side so that pressing one aid's program button simultaneously changes the other aid, so that both aids change background settings simultaneously.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] FM listening systems are now emerging with wireless receivers integrated with the use of hearing aids.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] A separate wireless microphone can be given to a partner to wear in a restaurant, in the car, during leisure time, in the shopping mall, at lectures, or during religious services.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] The voice is transmitted wirelessly to the hearing aids eliminating the effects of distance and background noise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] FM systems have shown to give the best speech understanding in noise of all available technologies.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] FM systems can also be hooked up to a TV or a stereo.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] 2.4 gigahertz Bluetooth connectivity is the most recent innovation in wireless interfacing for hearing instruments to audio sources such as TV streamers or Bluetooth enabled mobile phones.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Current hearing aids generally do not stream directly via Bluetooth but rather do so through a secondary streaming device (usually worn around the neck or in a pocket), this bluetooth enabled secondary device then streams wirelessly to the hearing aid but can only do so over a short distance.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] This technology can be applied to ready-to-wear devices (BTE, Mini BTE, RIE, etc.) or to custom made devices that fit directly into the ear.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] In developed countries FM systems are considered a cornerstone in the treatment of hearing loss in children.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] More and more adults discover the benefits of wireless FM systems as well, especially since transmitters with different microphone settings and Bluetooth for wireless cell phone communication have become available.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Many theatres and lecture halls are now equipped with assistive listening systems that transmit the sound directly from the stage; audience members can borrow suitable receivers and hear the program without background noise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] In some theatres and churches FM transmitters are available that work with the personal FM receivers of hearing instruments.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Most older hearing aids have only an omnidirectional microphone.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] An omnidirectional microphone amplifies sounds equally from all directions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] In contrast, a directional microphone amplifies sounds from one direction more than sounds from other directions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] This means that sounds originating from the direction the system is steered toward are amplified more than sounds coming from other directions.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] If the desired speech arrives from the direction of steering and the noise is from a different direction, then compared to an omnidirectional microphone, a directional microphone provides a better signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Improving the signal-to-noise ratio improves speech understanding in noise.
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Directional microphones have been found to be the second best method to improve the signal-to-noise ratio (the best method was an FM system, which locates the microphone near the mouth of the desired talker).
[src:australian-deaf-community/hearing-aid-p02] Many hearing aids have both an omnidirectional and a directional microphone mode.
